ce:section.ce:para:
The representative SEM images of Bi2O3 and Bi2O3/NCDs-2 composites are displayed in Fig. 2
                     . It is observed that the bare Bi2O3 possesses typically sheet-like morphology, and there are abundant voids on the surface. In contrast, the Bi2O3/NCDs-2 composites (Fig. 2b and 2c) have a spherical structure with a hollow interior. Fig. 2d exhibits the enlarged SEM image of the composites, from which we can clearly see that the Bi2O3/NCDs-2 hollow microspheres are assembled by a lot of porous nanosheets. In addition, the size of the nanosheets in Bi2O3/NCDs-2 composites is relatively smaller than that of bare Bi2O3. These results suggest that the NCDs have great effects on the microstructure of Bi2O3. It is known that NCDs are negatively charged due to the abundant functional groups on the surface [27,28]. Herein, the zeta potentials of NCDs and bare Bi2O3 are measured to be about −7.06 and +0.3099 mV, respectlvely. The NCDs will deposit on the surface of Bi2O3 nuclei and inhibit the growth of the Bi2O3 nanosheets. Moreover, the electrostatic interaction between NCDs and Bi3+ could also offer a driving force for the assembly of Bi2O3 nanosheets around NCDs to form a tightly packed architecture [19,27]. Such hollow and porous hierarchitecture can provide larger open channels for electrolytes, and is favourable for optimization the electrochemical properties of the Bi2O3/NCDs composites [18]. Further composition information of the Bi2O3/NCDs-2 hierarchitectures was acquired by the SEM mapping analysis (Fig. 3
                     ). The composites contain Bi, O, C and N elements, and those elements exhibit highly uniform distribution in the Bi2O3/NCDs-2 microspheres, which demonstrate that NCDs are homogeneously dispersed in the composites. The pore-size distribution of Bi2O3/NCDs-2 was analyzed by the Barrett-Joyner-Halenda method (Fig. 3f), and the corresponding pore diameters of the composites locate at about 4.5 and 55.2 nm.
